        <p><strong>Name:</strong> St John’s College</p>
        <p><strong>Location:</strong> St John’s College, Southsea, Portsmouth, Hampshire, UK</p>
        <p><strong>Year Built:</strong> [Insert year]</p>
        <p><strong>Architectural Style:</strong> Villa-style detached properties by Thomas Ellis Owen, architect and chief surveyor for Portsmouth in the mid-1800s.</p>
        <p><strong>Current Status:</strong> Abandoned, partially demolished, being redeveloped, stripped out</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>History</h2>
        <p>St John’s College was founded in [1908] as a boarding school for boys and girls aged 2-18 years. It later became known as a co-ed independent day and boarding school for children aged 4-18, located in the heart of Southsea. The college is renowned for its academic success and outstanding pastoral care.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Founded in 1843</strong> as a theological college by the Church of England.</li>
            <li>Expanded to offer educational programs, including teacher training.</li>
            <li>Served as a hospital in WWI during both World Wars.</li>
            <li>Closed in 1970 and repurposed for residential and office use.</li>
            <li>Popular among urban explorers for its architecture and history.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>About the Building</h2>
        <p>St John’s College in Southsea is a notable example of Edwardian architecture, featuring neo-Gothic elements such as pointed arches, decorative stonework, and turret-like towers. The main building, known as the "Castle" by students, has large, ornate windows that allow natural light to flood in.</p>
        <p><strong>Current State:</strong> Much of the building remains structurally intact. The area with sports facilities, including the sports hall, dance studio, and auditorium, is still in pristine condition, although demolition has begun in the rear. The sports hall and dance studios have been demolished, and the rest may not last long.</p>
    </section>

